dplyr concept map

Now that we’ve had some fun plotting data, we need to learn how to wrangle or manipulate data. This video will introduce six functions and in the next video, I will show you more details of the code in R Studio.

This concept map lays out the six functions I will introduce and what they would be used for.

Example data

garden_harvest

The data I will use throughout this video in the examples is the rawest form of the garden data a collected. There is a row for each time I weighed a vegetable. So, there could be multiple rows of the same vegetable on the same day, especially if there’s different varieties. Even when there’s not different varieties, there may be mutliple measurements. For example, if I weighed lettuce at lunch and dinner, which was pretty common.

These data, and most of the data we’ll see this semester, are referred to as tidy data, meaning each variable has its own column, each observation its own row, and each value has its own cell.

In R, the datasets are called data frames or tibbles. These have more specific meanings, which you will read about on your own.

Review of the pipe, `%>%

Connects sequential pieces of code.

Example using %>% with ggplot()

garden_harvest %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = weight)) +
  geom_histogram()

The pipe, %>%, gives us a way to connect sequential pieces of code, similar to the + in ggplot(). We read it as “and then.” It takes what is to the left of it and makes that the first argument of the function on the right. Since most of the functions we will use have the dataset as the first argument, the pipe is then a way to take the data to the left of it, which may have already been manipulated in some way, and pass it along to the next step.

We always press enter to create a new line after a pipe. This is for readability of the code.

In the example here, the garden_harvest data is then used in the ggplot() function.

dplyr verbs

select(): chooses which variables to keep

mutate(): adds one or more variables

filter(): keeps cases that meet certain criteria

arrange(): reorders the cases according to a specified criteria

summarize(): creates new summarized variables

group_by(): creates a grouped variable, often used in conjunction with summarize() to get a grouped summary

Images from R Studio Cheatsheets: https://rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/

There are six main data manipulation functions in the dplyr library, which is part of the tidyverse suite. The function names are verbs in the English language that help communicate what the do, so I sometimes refer to these functions as verbs. Each verb takes an input data frame along with additional arguments specifying the action, and returns a new data frame.

Variable-changing verbs: select()

select(): chooses which varaibles to keep 

garden_harvest %>% 
  select(vegetable, weight)

Let’s start with the verbs that change which variables (columns) are included in the data frame, but preserve the same set of cases (rows).

select() chooses which variables to keep, or put another way, deletes those variables that are not selected. To specify the variables, we can either list them out, or helper functions to specify the titles of the variables we wish to keep. I’ll talk about helper functions in the next video.

In the code shown here, we start with the garden_harvest data and then select the variables vegetable and weight. So only those two variables are in the resulting data set.

Variable-changing verbs: mutate()

mutate(): adds one or more variables 

garden_harvest %>% 
  mutate(wt_lbs = weight*0.00220462,
         over_1_lb = wt_lbs > 1)

mutate() adds one or more variables to the data frame. These new variables can be functions of other variables and can compare variables. The functions are applied to each case in the data. You can create more than one variable by separating them by commas. The name of the new variable is to the left of the equals sign.

In this code, we compute two new variables. The first, wt_lbs, converts the weights from grams to pounds. The second, over_1_lb, returns a TRUE if the harvest for that vegetable was over one pound. Otherwise it returns FALSE. Notice we can use the first variable we computed in the definition of the second.

Case-changing verbs: filter()

filter(): keeps cases that meet certain criteria 






garden_harvest %>% 
  filter(vegetable %in% c("tomatoes", "cucumber"),
         date >= ymd("2020-08-10"))
  • filter() deletes some of the cases by specifying which cases to keep. The table shows some of the operators that are used in filtering - see more in the cheatsheet or document that goes with this video. Separating arguments in a filter by a comma is the same as using and.

In the code here, we start with the garden_harvest data and then filter to the tomato and cucumber cases where the harvest date was on or after August 10th, 2020.

Case-changing verbs: arrange()

arrange(): reorders the cases according to a specified criteria 

garden_harvest %>% 
  arrange(vegetable, desc(weight))
  • arrange() reorders the cases according to a specified criteria. To sort in reverse order based on the variable x, use arrange(desc(x)). We can arrange the data by multiple variables. It will arrange by the first one first, then arranges by the next variable within the already arranged first variable. And so on.

We see an example of this in the code here. We start with the garden_harvest data and then arrange the cases in alphabetical order by vegetable. Then within each vegetable, the cases are arranged in descending order order of weight - heaviest to lightest harvests.

Variable & case-changing verbs: summarize()

summarize(): creates new summarized variables 

garden_harvest %>% 
  summarize(obs = n(),
            avg_weight = mean(weight),
            sd_weight = sd(weight))

summarize() takes an entire data frame as input and outputs a single row with one or more summary statistics. Like mutate(), we can have more than one new variable by separating them by commas, and giving them names to the left of the equals sign.

In this code, we take the garden_harvest data and then compute obs, which is how many observations there are, average weight and standard deviation of the weight.

Variable & case-changing verbs: group_by()

group_by(): creates a grouped variable 

garden_harvest %>% 
  group_by(date)
# A tibble: 421 x 5
# Groups:   date [66]

group_by() groups the cases of a data frame by a specified set of variables. When using group_by() alone, the size of the stored data frame does not actually change (neither the cases nor the variables change).

Most commonly this function is used before a summarize() to create grouped summaries. Whatever function is applied after the group_by() will be performed on each level or combination of levels of the variable(s).

In this code, the data doesn’t appear any different. If you would run that code in the console, you would see the output shown below the table. This means that the data are grouped by date and that there are 66 groups or dates.

Variable & case-changing verbs: group_by()

group_by(): often used in conjunction with summarize() to get a grouped summary 

garden_harvest %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarize(tot_each_date = sum(weight))

In this code we see an example of a grouped summary. The code starts with the garden_harvest data and then groups it by date. Then for each date, the weights are summed. So this table gives the total harvest in grams on each date.

Connecting verbs with the %>%

garden_harvest %>% 
  select(vegetable, date, weight) %>% 
  mutate(wt_lbs = weight*0.00220462) %>% 
  filter(vegetable %in% c("tomatoes", "peas")) %>% 
  group_by(vegetable, date) %>% 
  summarize(daily_wt_lbs = sum(wt_lbs)) %>% 
  mutate(cum_wt_lbs = cumsum(daily_wt_lbs)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = cum_wt_lbs, color = vegetable)) +
  geom_line()

Using the pipe, it is easy to connect pieces of code together and even to pipe into a ggplot.

In this code we do the following: - start with the garden_harvest data AND THEN - select vegetable, date, weight AND THEN - add a weight in pounds variable AND THEN - filter to tomato and pea vegetables AND THEN - group_by vegetable and date AND THEN - for each vegetable, date combination compute the total weight and call it daily_wt_lbs AND THEN - add a cumulative weight variable AND THEN - get ready plot it with date on the x-axis, cumulative weight in pounds on the y-axis, and colored by vegetable - and lastly plot it as a line

You can do many cool things already with these couple dozen plotting and wrangling functions I’ve shown you. How exciting, right?!

What happens to the data we’ve wrangled?

garden_harvest %>% 
  select(vegetable, date, weight) %>% 
  mutate(wt_lbs = weight*0.00220462) %>% 
  filter(vegetable %in% c("tomatoes", "peas")) %>% 
  group_by(vegetable, date) %>% 
  summarize(daily_wt_lbs = sum(wt_lbs)) %>% 
  mutate(cum_wt_lbs = cumsum(daily_wt_lbs))


garden_harvest

One more thing before we finish. As we’re piping code together, it’s important to remember that this doesn’t change your original data.

If I look at garden_harvest after doing all the piped code, it still looks the same.

What happens to the data we’ve wrangled?

daily_smry_tomato_pea <- garden_harvest %>% 
  select(vegetable, date, weight) %>% 
  mutate(wt_lbs = weight*0.00220462) %>% 
  filter(vegetable %in% c("tomatoes", "peas")) %>% 
  group_by(vegetable, date) %>% 
  summarize(daily_wt_lbs = sum(wt_lbs)) %>% 
  mutate(cum_wt_lbs = cumsum(daily_wt_lbs))

daily_smry_tomato_pea

If you do a lot of wrangling and you want to access that data more than once, then save it to a new dataset. Then, you can use that dataset in other code. Here I’ve saved the wrangled data to daily_smry_tomato_pea
